You know what makes me sad sometimes. As a jj academy owner I’ve learned that so many parents listen to their kids opinions on things like martial arts. Some people tell me oh my 5y/o doesn’t like it anymore. First thought in my mind “why are you listening to a 5y/o do you not know whats good or bad for him/her”. My own son tells me often that he doesn’t wanna train. Its natural for kids and just for human beings in general. We don’t wanna do uncomfortable stuff. Im not trying to attack anyone, if you one of those Im not intending to attack in fact the opposite I hope some who thought that way will change their mind wherever you live. Everyone has their own lives to live, you’re responsible for your life. But if my son tells me he doesn’t wanna eat healthy foods and just want ice creams all day, he’s not getting ice creams. Why? Cause Im an adult that knows what good or whats bad for him. I don’t say “oh my son doesn’t like healthy food no more” nor do I allow him to play video games and watch tv all day just cause he wants. I know its bad and I’ll chose what he will do until he grows up and go on free sail. Until then its my job to teach him that life is hard so his adulthood would be easier. World isn’t full of rainbows and sunshines and I know jiu jitsu is a great martial art for one on one fight. Regardless he likes it or not it’s mandatory for him. Because I know how much he will benefit from training. So parents my advice don’t go by narrative of your kids, I get it you love them and I understand I love too but sometimes because of the love people make wrong decisions that later in life they will realize but will be too late. 

Have you noticed how many rich men who went through poverty and hard life to get where they are end up having super spoiled kids who never achieve anything. Only rare cases when they actually do. Why? Because they spoil them out of love. Don’t spoil them. Instead of feeding them the fish teach them how to fish. Make sure they do what’s good for them. They’ll thank you later. 

Martial arts is one of the best ways to teach kids about life. I 100% believe that. I learned more about life on the mats than in school. #bjj #jiujitsu

As a coach and father of my student I caught myself thinking when I was at the tournament coaching students what parents think when they see their child go through Gi check and wait at the bull pen before the officials take them to the mats to fight. Its a very nervous feeling, more nervous than I compete. 

I can control how I feel with right mindset when I compete but your kids they’re on their own. You guide them you motivate them but they will have to fight that battle themselves in their own heads. I think its a very good thing for them, they learn at young age how life is. They will have to go on their own scared and figure out the way. The more you do it the more comfortable you become with it. While most people would be afraid to take a step to try, you already boiling in these waters and trying to adapt. 

As a parent it’s nervous to see your little child to be somewhere and you have to watch on the side. You wanna hug them and tell them here lets go home, I buy you a toy and some treats instead you’re teaching them hard valuable lessons in a safe environment. They might cry if they lose cause nobody likes to lose or be humiliated in-front of people but you have to teach them son/daughter in life things are not always gonna go as you expect you have to learn how to adapt and deal with things emotionally. Teach them how to control their emotions. Be there to support them explain them like a friend. These are hard lessons that they must learn but super beneficial for them. 

Running away from the problem doesn’t fix it. “Oh you don’t like to lose ok daddy wont take you there anymore “ where this midset gonna get you in life? Nowhere. Always hiding.
Attack your fears, the more you do it the lesser scary they are. When I see my son or students competing I tell myself I can’t control the outcome I can only control things during preparation and after the event is done. If he lost good you learned something, if you won good you learned something. Win win situation as long as you analyze , work on mistakes and try again with a lil bit more experience this time. 

#bjj #bjjkids #bjjkidsclass #coaching

Mats teach you valuable lessons in life.
Life is full of ups and downs. Emotionally happy moments and tough heart breaking moments. On the mats you get good days and bad days so to speak. Most people consider good days when they crush everyone and bad days when things didn’t click as much so you lost more than won. They say sometimes you are a hammer and sometimes you’re a nail. I think you have to have attitude that both of these experiences are positive ones because you learn when you lose the most. You understand that you live another day to try. You learn humility, your ego is at check. When overtime you overcome tough situations on the mats you get break through. Same in life its a lesson that if you work harder you get ahead. You have tough situations in life you try not to dwell on them because it will make life more stressful. You just live another day to try. Through martial arts you learn that failure is your biggest teacher. When you analyze your failures and try again overtime you succeed. On the mats you can have 2 people working hard and one works much harder but another one works hard maybe less physically but works smarter and he gets ahead. You learn that in life its not enough just to work hard you gotta work smart. A lot of people can work hard what separates you is how smart your hard work is. On the mats you learn that any skill can be learned as long as you put an effort. You learn that with consistency overtime comes success. You learn that things doesn’t happen overnight and you have to be patient. You learn that your health is important the better you take care of your health the better results you will have because in healthy body healthy mind. Also you learn on the mats respect, honor and dignity you treat people better than once before. Mats teach you to be calm in tough situations. Competition teaches you how to deal with nerves, what should you do when you feel super nervous how to calm down. There are so many things. It’s truly the school of life. I keep saying this that mats taught me more lessons about life than school itself 100% #bjjlifestlye #jiujitsulife

My first full match from recent competition. It was nice to come back to competition after long break. Almost a year I think or a bit less. Honestly I didn’t wanna compete because I dont have enough energy to train full time properly like competitors should train. Im more focused on my students and teaching them. But I made up my mind that regardless if I’m not training hard I’ll just go and compete for fun. Win or lose whatever always been my mindset as long as I give my best in competition and in the training room. This time I don’t have luxury to focus on myself training twice per day instead I do what I can and try to have fun competing. Usually I fight medium heavy guys while Im 1-2lbs away from middle weight lol just simply because I didn’t wanna worry about being on weight. I always fought bigger guys and this time felt like I was so much stronger than my opponents (even though Im not in great shape). So maybe now I’ll try more in middle weight division to see how I can do there. Also being a coach was totally different experience coaching everyone and then competing yourself. Honestly I left all my nerves and voice while coaching that when it was time to compete I was not nervous I was happy super sleepy but happy that finally i can fight now😅 it was an interesting experience. Thank you everyone for the support 🤝 #bjj #jiujitsu #checkmatbjj

2014 Audi R8 Spyder (convertible) model.

Honestly never been like a big fan of Audi I always kinda liked Rs6s but since I watched iron man movie R8 was definitely my favorite looking Audi even though I haven’t driven one before. This exact car I rented on Turo and it was with dual clutch transmission paired with V10 engine. Honestly I fell in love right away. Im no expert but I believe it had 5.2 liter V10 with a lil bit over 500hp and around 400lb-ft torque. Car felt super fast and handling was amazing. I felt like power was like perfectly enough for me to enjoy the torque speed and handling. The only downside side was that stock exhaust (was not loud enough imo) I think upgraded exhaust would make it even more better experience. Still I have had an amazing experience exceeding all expectations and now one day I want to get exact same year R8 with V10 but with hard top roof. Even though newer R8 faster but I enjoy styling of an older model. 
R8 is pretty much cheaper version of Lamborghini because it shares same engine as Lamborghini Huracan I believe. Very emotional car. I pretty much lived in it those 2 days while I was renting it 😅 I just wanted to constantly downshift and hear that v10. Music to my ears 🎶 💨

#audir8 #audiv10 #r8v10 #vagcars
Honestly that felt like so fast. Newer cars with similar hp don’t feel as fast and emotional 🚗 I think this car had like 560whp if I’m not mistaken. Definitely a car to have #corvette #c6z06 #v8power

Throwback to Malaysia 🇲🇾 Kota Kinabalu island 🏝️ Probably my longest vacation I’ve ever had lol this was right before opening @neezamjj we took 40 day vacation. Honestly at some point I was going nuts because I wasn’t just used to chilling for so long. I was mad at myself because thinking why am I not enjoying these beautiful places but then I figured that my body was freaking out due to not being in normal routine. I found jiu jitsu gym not far where we lived and then it became one of my favorite vacations. Eat, chill, train jiu jitsu and cheap coconuts 😎. Fun times, gotta visit one day. But one thing for sure no matter where you go you always miss your home and daily routine. So the main lesson is to appreciate what you have 🤝 its fun to explore but without being great full it’s all pointless.

 #travel #bjj #malaysia
